--------------------------------
16 SECTIONS
--------------------------------

01. SOCIAL PROOF
	- never enough
	- testimonials
	- sprinkle them everywhere
	- avatar 1 -> objection 1
	- avatar 2 -> objection 2
	- avatar 3 -> objection 3
	- text, screenshot, videos...
	- layout:
		- headline
		- content
		- picture
		- name

02. GUARANTEE
	- absolute must
	- it addresses the biggest objection of all: 
		- fear, risk, uncertanty

03. MODULE BREAKDOWN (#6)
	- like table of contents for a course, but not quite
	- module 1 is..., module 2 is..., etc...
	- module headline + bullet list
	- divide your offer in smaller deliverables, and define them as modules
	- suppose each module is a book... would you buy that module by the headline only?
	- use action words in the title (e.g. activate, discover, remove...)
	- maybe add testimonials related to each module
	- bullets:
		- "discover how to ___ so that ___"
		- "the secret to ___"
		- "how to ___ without ___"
		- "the sneaky ___"
		- "the quickest/easiest/fastest ___"
		- "the single most ___"
		- "the truth about ___"
		- "what ___ don't tell you about ___"
	- the power of curiosity:
		- "the one secret..."
		- "the simple strategy on page 24 that will..."

04. BONUSES (#11)
	- put after the price
	- after they see the price, they go into cost/benefit evaluation mode
	- use the bonuses to pump the value of the offer
	- the bonuses are to address their biggest objection
	- bonuses:
		- write "BONUS"
		- list with numbers
		- demonstate value in the name
		- add price value
		- product image
		- copy
	- chunk up bonuses x bundle
	- e.g. "Bonuse #3. The quick-start bonus bundle"

05. FAQ (#14)
	- address the objections behind the questions
	- don't "answer" the question, discredit the belief
	- maybe agree, and amplify

06. "EARNING" DISCLAIMER (#15) if relevant

07. FOOTER (#16)
	- copyright
	- privaci policy
	- terms
	- earning disclaimer

08. CTA/PRICING (#9)
	- an entire section when you put a clear call to action
	- eg. entirely for free for 30 days, then $49/month
	- lead with your installment plan
		- then you offer to save when pay in full
		- eg. save 23% when you pay in full
		- use "sold out" for offers
		- 12 installment of $297 > one payment $14,997 (sold out?)... if you upgrade to full payment you save X%
	- avoid words like: pay, payment, price, cost, purhcase (use these when you talk about competitor alternatives)
	- use words like: investment, insatallment, enroll, register, join

09. THE PRICING TABLE (#8)
	- if applicable
	- tell what's included and whats not (comparing offers)

10. THE PRICING CONVERSATION (#7)
	- befor the price
	- "ok, ok, so how much is it?"
	- meet them where they at
		- asking the question
		- most people have inner discussions about price
	- emotional decision, and price is not really and emotional decision
	- explain how we came to the price, while also making it sound so cheap
	- apples and oranges comparison
		- compare app. to orang. in copy
		- reading a book vs 101 training
		- if you sell 101 training, make your case and influence them on why 101 training is the best
	- show people you are an unicorn
	- discount, tell price before and after the offer
	- it's a small investment in yourself that pays huge dividends in your future (frame size)

11. THE CHOICE (#13)
	- a CTA is a choice
	- now your readers must make a choice
	- make their life easy
		- tell them they have a choice
		- narrowing that choice into two options
	1. identify your two choices (invest and not invest)
	2. anchor benefit to investing
	3. anchor consequence to not invest
	4. ask them to choose
	- the energy: "look, we've had our fun, but it's time to get real"
	- add urgency to choice

12. EMPATHY AND WARNING (#2)
	- people are on your salespage because they have a problem (discomfort)
	- a problem is the gap between dream and reality
	- show you understand their problem
	- you are not pain agitating, they are already in pain
	- you gotta feel it, if you wanna heal it
	- energy: "oh man, i totally get it. it suchs. and if you'r like my other clients, you probably also feel..."

	1. external
		- speak to the external problem
		- the event that's causing the problem
	2. internal 
		- because of the EP, they have an internal state
		- "because of this, you feel frustrated, stuck ..." (list negative emotions) 
		- use their emotions to speak back to them the converstaions they are having inside their head (toughts)
	3. culprit
		- identify the cause or culprit
		- what actually is causing the problem (maybe the exact opposite of your offer)
	4. warning
		- what will hapen in the future if thei problem isn't solved? if you don't get rid of the culprit?

13. INTRODUCE SOLUTION (#3)
	- the solution is your veicle
	- change the world so they can see things your way

14. INTRODUCING YOUR OFFER (#4)
	- "introducing [product name]"
	- product image
	- people trust specialists, not generalists
	- what it is (process) - "8 week coaching group that will..."
	- tell me what it is
	- bullepoint - high level stuff (maybe based on modules headlines)

15. RECAPING THE OFFER (#12)
	- "so, lets recap!"
	- when you join ... you'll get ...
	- you gett all of this (value: $$$)
	- bullet points

16. TOP OF SALES PAGE (#13)
	- logo, timer, cta button
	- headling (get their attention so they keep reading) (mega-headline)
	- you sales page is a series of headlines - master headlines (bullet points)
	- the mega headline
		- sums up everything
		- makes the promise
		- has the answer
		- addresses the objections
		- sells the product
	- if you have preselling (content, emails, contacts...) the headline isn't a make or break situation
	- the energy is: excitement
	- "they laughed when i sat down at the piano. but when i started to play!" (redemption, ego, status, prove the haters wrong)
	- "discover how to attract your first 100 leads that actually want to buy your stuff"
	- specific, simple, relatable, tangible, duable, transformation (actually, exactly)
	- for lead magnets, don't say freebies. say training, cheatsheet, workshop, masterclass
	- headline: all caps or first letter capped, sans-serif
	- what they wish? ("geeny, i wish...")
	- what they can tangibly do to satisfy internal wishes (feelings)
	- what actions and activities and results will give them fulfillment
	- what would give them respect
